# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: hungarian-algorithm
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] The **assignment problem** is a fundamental combinatorial optimization problem.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] that may vary depending on the agent-task assignment.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] of maximum size, in which the sum of weights of the edges is minimum.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] If the numbers of agents and tasks are equal, then the problem is called **balanced assignment**, and the graph-theoretic version is called **minimum-cost perfect matching**.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] Otherwise, it is called **unbalanced assignment**.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] If the total cost of the assignment for all tasks is equal to the sum of the costs for each agent (or the sum of the costs for each task, which is the same thing in this case), then the problem is called **linear assignment**.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] Commonly, when speaking of the *assignment problem* without any additional qualification, then the *linear balanced assignment problem* is meant.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] Suppose that a taxi firm has three taxis (the agents) available, and three customers (the tasks) wishing to be picked up as soon as possible.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] The firm prides itself on speedy pickups, so for each taxi the "cost" of picking up a particular customer will depend on the time taken for the taxi to reach the pickup point.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] This is a *balanced assignment* problem.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] Its solution is whichever combination of taxis and customers results in the least total cost.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] Now, suppose that there are *four* taxis available, but still only three customers.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] This is an *unbalanced assignment* problem.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] One way to solve it is to invent a fourth dummy task, perhaps called "sitting still doing nothing", with a cost of 0 for the taxi assigned to it.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] This reduces the problem to a balanced assignment problem, which can then be solved in the usual way and still give the best solution to the problem.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] Similar adjustments can be done in order to allow more tasks than agents, tasks to which multiple agents must be assigned (for instance, a group of more customers than will fit in one taxi), or maximizing profit rather than minimizing cost.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] The problem is "linear" because the cost function to be optimized as well as all the constraints contain only linear terms.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] A naive solution for the assignment problem is to check all the assignments and calculate the cost of each one.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] This may be very inefficient since, with *n* agents and *n* tasks, there are *n*!
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] (factorial of *n*) different assignments.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] Another naive solution is to greedily assign the pair with the smallest cost first, and remove the vertices; then, among the remaining vertices, assign the pair with the smallest cost; and so on.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] This algorithm may yield a non-optimal solution.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] The greedy algorithm would assign Task 1 to Alice and Task 2 to George, for a total cost of 9, but the reverse assignment has a total cost of 7.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] Fortunately, there are many algorithms for finding the optimal assignment in time polynomial in *n*.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] The assignment problem is a special case of the transportation problem, which is a special case of the minimum cost flow problem, which in turn is a special case of a linear program.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] While it is possible to solve any of these problems using the simplex algorithm, or in worst-case polynomial time using the ellipsoid method, each specialization has a smaller solution space and thus more efficient algorithms designed to take advantage of its special structure.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] In the balanced assignment problem, both parts of the bipartite graph have the same number of vertices, denoted by *n*.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] One of the first polynomial-time algorithms for balanced assignment was the Hungarian algorithm.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] It is a *global* algorithm – it is based on improving a matching along augmenting paths (alternating paths between unmatched vertices).
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] Its run-time complexity, when using Fibonacci heaps, is $O(mn+n^{2}\log n)$ , where *m* is the number of edges.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] This is currently the fastest run-time of a strongly polynomial algorithm for this problem.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] Some variants of the Hungarian algorithm also benefit from parallel computing, including GPU acceleration.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] If all weights are integers, then the run-time can be improved to $O(mn+n^{2}\log \log n)$ , but the resulting algorithm is only weakly polynomial.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] If the weights are integers, and all weights are at most *C* (where *C*>1 is some integer), then the problem can be solved in $O(m{\sqrt {n}}\log(n\cdot C))$ weakly-polynomial time in a method called *weight scaling*.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] In addition to the global methods, there are *local methods* which are based on finding local updates (rather than full augmenting paths).
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] These methods have worse asymptotic runtime guarantees, but they often work better in practice.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] These algorithms are called auction algorithms, push-relabel algorithms, or preflow-push algorithms.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] Some of these algorithms were shown to be equivalent.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] Some of the local methods assume that the graph admits a *perfect matching*; if this is not the case, then some of these methods might run forever.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] A simple technical way to solve this problem is to extend the input graph to a *complete bipartite graph,* by adding artificial edges with very large weights.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] These weights should exceed the weights of all existing matchings, to prevent appearance of artificial edges in the possible solution.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] As shown by Mulmuley, Vazirani and Vazirani, the problem of minimum weight perfect matching is converted to finding minors in the adjacency matrix of a graph.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] Using the isolation lemma, a minimum weight perfect matching in a graph can be found with probability at least 1⁄2.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] For a graph with *n* vertices, it requires $O(\log ^{2}(n))$ time.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] In the unbalanced assignment problem, the larger part of the bipartite graph has *n* vertices and the smaller part has *r*<*n* vertices.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] There is also a constant *s* which is at most the cardinality of a maximum matching in the graph.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] The goal is to find a minimum-cost matching of size exactly *s*.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] The most common case is the case in which the graph admits a one-sided-perfect matching (i.e., a matching of size *r*), and *s*=*r*.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] Unbalanced assignment can be reduced to a balanced assignment.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] The naive reduction is to add $n-r$ new vertices to the smaller part and connect them to the larger part using edges of cost 0.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] However, this requires $n(n-r)$ new edges.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] A more efficient reduction is called the *doubling technique*.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] Here, a new graph *G'* is built from two copies of the original graph *G*: a forward copy *Gf* and a backward copy *Gb.* The backward copy is "flipped", so that, in each side of *G'*, there are now *n*+*r* vertices.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] All in all, at most $n+r$ new edges are required.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] The resulting graph always has a perfect matching of size $n+r$ .
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] A minimum-cost perfect matching in this graph must consist of minimum-cost maximum-cardinality matchings in *Gf* and *Gb.* The main problem with this doubling technique is that there is no speed gain when $r\ll n$ .
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] Instead of using reduction, the unbalanced assignment problem can be solved by directly generalizing existing algorithms for balanced assignment.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] The Hungarian algorithm can be generalized to solve the problem in $O(ms+s^{2}\log r)$ strongly-polynomial time.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] In particular, if *s*=*r* then the runtime is $O(mr+r^{2}\log r)$ .
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] If the weights are integers, then Thorup's method can be used to get a runtime of $O(ms+s^{2}\log \log r)$ .
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] The assignment problem can be solved by presenting it as a linear program.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] For convenience we will present the maximization problem.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] Each edge (*i*,*j*), where *i* is in A and *j* is in T, has a weight ${\textstyle w_{ij}}$ .
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] For each edge ⁠ $(i,j)$ ⁠ we have a variable ${\textstyle x_{ij}}$ .
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] The total weight of the matching is: $\sum _{(i,j)\in A\times T}w_{ij}x_{ij}$ .
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] The goal is to find a maximum-weight perfect matching.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] However, we can solve it without the integrality constraints (i.e., drop the last constraint), using standard methods for solving continuous linear programs.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] While this formulation allows also fractional variable values, in this special case, the LP always has an optimal solution where the variables take integer values.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] This is because the constraint matrix of the fractional LP is totally unimodular – it satisfies the four conditions of Hoffman and Gale.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] Other approaches for the assignment problem exist and are reviewed by Duan and Pettie (see Table II).
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] Their work proposes an approximation algorithm for the assignment problem (and the more general maximum-weight matching problem), which runs in linear time for any fixed error bound.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] In the basic assignment problem, each agent is assigned to at most one task and each task is assigned to at most one agent.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] In the **many-to-many assignment problem**, each agent *i* may take up to *ci* tasks (*ci* is called the agent's *capacity*), and each task *j* may be taken by up to *dj* agents simultaneously (*dj* is called the task's *capacity*).
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] If the sums of capacities in both sides are equal ( $\sum _{i}c_{i}=\sum _{j}d_{j}$ ), then the problem is *balanced*, and the goal is to find a perfect matching (assign exactly *ci* tasks to each agent *i* and exactly *dj* agents to each task *j*) such that the total cost is as small as possible.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] The problem can be solved by reduction to the minimum cost network flow problem.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] An integral maximum flow of minimum cost can be found in polynomial time; see network flow problem.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] Every integral maximum flow in this network corresponds to a matching in which at most *ci* tasks are assigned to each agent *i* and at most *dj* agents are assigned to each task *j* (in the balanced case, exactly *ci* tasks are assigned to *i* and exactly *dj* agents are assigned to *j*).
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] A min-cost maximum flow corresponds to a min-cost assignment.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] When phrased as a graph theory problem, the assignment problem can be extended from bipartite graphs to arbitrary graphs.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] The corresponding problem, of finding a matching in a weighted graph where the sum of weights is maximized, is called the maximum-weight matching problem.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] Another generalization of the assignment problem is extending the number of sets to be matched from two to many.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] So that rather than matching agents to tasks, the problem is extended to matching agents to tasks to time intervals to locations.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/assignment-problem] This results in Multidimensional assignment problem.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/bipartite-graph] In the mathematical field of graph theory, a **bipartite graph** (or **bigraph**) is a graph whose vertices can be divided into two disjoint and independent sets U and V , that is, every edge connects a vertex in U to one in V .
[src:hungarian-algorithm/bipartite-graph] Vertex sets U and V are usually called the *parts* of the graph.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/bipartite-graph] Equivalently, a bipartite graph is a graph that does not contain any odd-length cycles.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/bipartite-graph] The two sets U and V may be thought of as a coloring of the graph with two colors: if one colors all nodes in U blue, and all nodes in V red, each edge has endpoints of differing colors, as is required in the graph coloring problem.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/bipartite-graph] In contrast, such a coloring is impossible in the case of a non-bipartite graph, such as a triangle: after one node is colored blue and another red, the third vertex of the triangle is connected to vertices of both colors, preventing it from being assigned either color.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/bipartite-graph] One often writes $G=(U,V,E)$ to denote a bipartite graph whose partition has the parts U and V , with E denoting the edges of the graph.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/bipartite-graph] If a bipartite graph is not connected, it may have more than one bipartition; in this case, the $(U,V,E)$ notation is helpful in specifying one particular bipartition that may be of importance in an application.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/bipartite-graph] If $|U|=|V|$ , that is, if the two subsets have equal cardinality, then G is called a *balanced* bipartite graph.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/bipartite-graph] If all vertices on the same side of the bipartition have the same degree, then G is called biregular.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/bipartite-graph] When modelling relations between two different classes of objects, bipartite graphs very often arise naturally.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/bipartite-graph] For instance, a graph of football players and clubs, with an edge between a player and a club if the player has played for that club, is a natural example of an *affiliation network*, a type of bipartite graph used in social network analysis.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/bipartite-graph] This problem can be modeled as a dominating set problem in a bipartite graph that has a vertex for each train and each station and an edge for each pair of a station and a train that stops at that station.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/bipartite-graph] In bipartite graphs, the size of minimum vertex cover is equal to the size of the maximum matching; this is Kőnig's theorem.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/bipartite-graph] An alternative and equivalent form of this theorem is that the size of the maximum independent set plus the size of the maximum matching is equal to the number of vertices.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/bipartite-graph] In any graph without isolated vertices the size of the minimum edge cover plus the size of a maximum matching equals the number of vertices.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/bipartite-graph] Combining this equality with Kőnig's theorem leads to the facts that, in bipartite graphs, the size of the minimum edge cover is equal to the size of the maximum independent set, and the size of the minimum edge cover plus the size of the minimum vertex cover is equal to the number of vertices.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/bipartite-graph] Another class of related results concerns perfect graphs: every bipartite graph, the complement of every bipartite graph, the line graph of every bipartite graph, and the complement of the line graph of every bipartite graph, are all perfect.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/bipartite-graph] Perfection of bipartite graphs is easy to see (their chromatic number is two and their maximum clique size is also two) but perfection of the complements of bipartite graphs is less trivial, and is another restatement of Kőnig's theorem.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/bipartite-graph] This was one of the results that motivated the initial definition of perfect graphs.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/bipartite-graph] The bipartite graphs, line graphs of bipartite graphs, and their complements form four out of the five basic classes of perfect graphs used in the proof of the strong perfect graph theorem.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/bipartite-graph] It follows that any subgraph of a bipartite graph is also bipartite because it cannot gain an odd cycle.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/bipartite-graph] For a vertex, the number of adjacent vertices is called the degree of the vertex and is denoted $\deg v$ .
[src:hungarian-algorithm/bipartite-graph] The degree sequence of a bipartite graph is the pair of lists each containing the degrees of the two parts U and V .
[src:hungarian-algorithm/bipartite-graph] Isomorphic bipartite graphs have the same degree sequence.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/bipartite-graph] However, the degree sequence does not, in general, uniquely identify a bipartite graph; in some cases, non-isomorphic bipartite graphs may have the same degree sequence.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/bipartite-graph] The bipartite realization problem is the problem of finding a simple bipartite graph with the degree sequence being two given lists of natural numbers.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/bipartite-graph] The biadjacency matrix of a bipartite graph $(U,V,E)$ is a (0,1) matrix of size $|U|\times |V|$ that has a one for each pair of adjacent vertices and a zero for nonadjacent vertices.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/bipartite-graph] Biadjacency matrices may be used to describe equivalences between bipartite graphs, hypergraphs, and directed graphs.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/bipartite-graph] A hypergraph is a combinatorial structure that, like an undirected graph, has vertices and edges, but in which the edges may be arbitrary sets of vertices rather than having to have exactly two endpoints.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/bipartite-graph] A bipartite graph $(U,V,E)$ may be used to model a hypergraph in which U is the set of vertices of the hypergraph, V is the set of hyperedges, and E contains an edge from a hypergraph vertex v to a hypergraph edge e exactly when v is one of the endpoints of e.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/bipartite-graph] Under this correspondence, the biadjacency matrices of bipartite graphs are exactly the incidence matrices of the corresponding hypergraphs.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/bipartite-graph] A similar reinterpretation of adjacency matrices may be used to show a one-to-one correspondence between directed graphs (on a given number of labeled vertices, allowing self-loops) and balanced bipartite graphs, with the same number of vertices on both sides of the bipartition.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/bipartite-graph] For, the adjacency matrix of a directed graph with n vertices can be any (0,1) matrix of size $n\times n$ , which can then be reinterpreted as the adjacency matrix of a bipartite graph with n vertices on each side of its bipartition.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/bipartite-graph] In this construction, the bipartite graph is the bipartite double cover of the directed graph.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/bipartite-graph] It is possible to test whether a graph is bipartite, and to return either a two-coloring (if it is bipartite) or an odd cycle (if it is not) in linear time, using depth-first search (DFS).
[src:hungarian-algorithm/bipartite-graph] The main idea is to assign to each vertex the color that differs from the color of its parent in the DFS forest, assigning colors in a preorder traversal of the depth-first-search forest.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/bipartite-graph] This will necessarily provide a two-coloring of the spanning forest consisting of the edges connecting vertices to their parents, but it may not properly color some of the non-forest edges.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/bipartite-graph] In a DFS forest, one of the two endpoints of every non-forest edge is an ancestor of the other endpoint, and when the depth first search discovers an edge of this type it should check that these two vertices have different colors.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/bipartite-graph] If they do not, then the path in the forest from ancestor to descendant, together with the miscolored edge, form an odd cycle, which is returned from the algorithm together with the result that the graph is not bipartite.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/bipartite-graph] However, if the algorithm terminates without detecting an odd cycle of this type, then every edge must be properly colored, and the algorithm returns the coloring together with the result that the graph is bipartite.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/bipartite-graph] Alternatively, a similar procedure may be used with breadth-first search in place of DFS.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/bipartite-graph] Again, each node is given the opposite color to its parent in the search forest, in breadth-first order.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/bipartite-graph] If, when a vertex is colored, there exists an edge connecting it to a previously-colored vertex with the same color, then this edge together with the paths in the breadth-first search forest connecting its two endpoints to their lowest common ancestor forms an odd cycle.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/bipartite-graph] If the algorithm terminates without finding an odd cycle in this way, then it must have found a proper coloring, and can safely conclude that the graph is bipartite.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/bipartite-graph] Odd cycle transversal is an NP-complete algorithmic problem that asks, given a graph *G* = (*V*,*E*) and a number *k*, whether there exists a set of *k* vertices whose removal from *G* would cause the resulting graph to be bipartite.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/bipartite-graph] The problem is fixed-parameter tractable, meaning that there is an algorithm whose running time can be bounded by a polynomial function of the size of the graph multiplied by a larger function of *k*.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/bipartite-graph] The name *odd cycle transversal* comes from the fact that a graph is bipartite if and only if it has no odd cycles.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/bipartite-graph] Hence, to delete vertices from a graph in order to obtain a bipartite graph, one needs to "hit all odd cycle", or find a so-called odd cycle transversal set.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/bipartite-graph] In the illustration, every odd cycle in the graph contains the blue (the bottommost) vertices, so removing those vertices kills all odd cycles and leaves a bipartite graph.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/bipartite-graph] The *edge bipartization* problem is the algorithmic problem of deleting as few edges as possible to make a graph bipartite and is also an important problem in graph modification algorithmics.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/bipartite-graph] This problem is also fixed-parameter tractable, and can be solved in time ${\textstyle O\left(2^{k}m^{2}\right)}$ , where *k* is the number of edges to delete and *m* is the number of edges in the input graph.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/bipartite-graph] A matching in a graph is a subset of its edges, no two of which share an endpoint.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/bipartite-graph] Polynomial time algorithms are known for many algorithmic problems on matchings, including maximum matching (finding a matching that uses as many edges as possible), maximum-weight matching, and stable marriage.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/bipartite-graph] In many cases, matching problems are simpler to solve on bipartite graphs than on non-bipartite graphs, and many matching algorithms such as the Hopcroft–Karp algorithm for maximum-cardinality matching work correctly only on bipartite inputs.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/bipartite-graph] As a simple example, suppose that a set P of people are all seeking jobs from among a set J of jobs, with not all people suitable for all jobs.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/bipartite-graph] This situation can be modeled as a bipartite graph $(P,J,E)$ where an edge connects each job-seeker with each suitable job.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/bipartite-graph] A perfect matching describes a way of simultaneously satisfying all job-seekers and filling all jobs; Hall's marriage theorem provides a characterization of the bipartite graphs which allow perfect matchings.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/bipartite-graph] The National Resident Matching Program applies graph matching methods to solve this problem for U.S. medical student job-seekers and hospital residency jobs.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/bipartite-graph] The Dulmage–Mendelsohn decomposition is a structural decomposition of bipartite graphs that is useful in finding maximum matchings.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/bipartite-graph] Bipartite graphs are extensively used in modern coding theory, especially to decode codewords received from the channel.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/bipartite-graph] Factor graphs and Tanner graphs are examples of this.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/bipartite-graph] A Tanner graph is a bipartite graph in which the vertices on one side of the bipartition represent digits of a codeword, and the vertices on the other side represent combinations of digits that are expected to sum to zero in a codeword without errors.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/bipartite-graph] A factor graph is a closely related belief network used for probabilistic decoding of LDPC and turbo codes.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/bipartite-graph] In computer science, a Petri net is a mathematical modeling tool used in analysis and simulations of concurrent systems.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/bipartite-graph] A system is modeled as a bipartite directed graph with two sets of nodes: A set of "place" nodes that contain resources, and a set of "event" nodes which generate and/or consume resources.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/bipartite-graph] There are additional constraints on the nodes and edges that constrain the behavior of the system.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/bipartite-graph] Petri nets utilize the properties of bipartite directed graphs and other properties to allow mathematical proofs of the behavior of systems while also allowing easy implementation of simulations of the system.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/bipartite-graph] In projective geometry, Levi graphs are a form of bipartite graph used to model the incidences between points and lines in a configuration.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/bipartite-graph] Corresponding to the geometric property of points and lines that every two lines meet in at most one point and every two points be connected with a single line, Levi graphs necessarily do not contain any cycles of length four, so their girth must be six or more.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] The **Hungarian algorithm** or **Hungarian method** is a combinatorial optimization algorithm that solves the assignment problem in polynomial time and which anticipated later primal–dual methods.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] It was developed and published in 1955 by Harold Kuhn, who gave it the name "Hungarian method" because the algorithm was largely based on the earlier works of two Hungarian mathematicians, Dénes Kőnig and Jenő Egerváry.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] However, in 2006 it was discovered that Carl Gustav Jacobi had solved the assignment problem in the 19th century, and the solution had been published posthumously in 1890 in Latin.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] James Munkres reviewed the algorithm in 1957 and observed that it is (strongly) polynomial.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] Since then the algorithm has been known also as the **Kuhn–Munkres algorithm** or **Munkres assignment algorithm**.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] The time complexity of the original algorithm was $O(n^{4})$ , however Edmonds and Karp, and independently Tomizawa, noticed that it can be modified to achieve an $O(n^{3})$ running time.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] Ford and Fulkerson extended the method to general maximum flow problems in form of the Ford–Fulkerson algorithm.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] In this simple example, there are three workers: Alice, Bob and Carol.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] One of them has to clean the bathroom, another sweep the floors and the third washes the windows, but they each demand different pay for the various tasks.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] The problem is to find the lowest-cost way to assign the jobs.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] The problem can be represented in a matrix of the costs of the workers doing the jobs.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] The Hungarian method, when applied to the above table, would give the minimum cost: this is $15, achieved by having Alice clean the bathroom, Carol sweep the floors, and Bob wash the windows.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] In the matrix formulation, we are given an *n*×*n* matrix, where the element in the *i*-th row and *j*-th column represents the cost of assigning the *j*-th job to the *i*-th worker.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] We have to find an assignment of the jobs to the workers, such that each job is assigned to one worker and each worker is assigned one job, such that the total cost of assignment is minimum.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] If the goal is to find the assignment that yields the *maximum* cost, the problem can be solved by negating the cost matrix *C*.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] The algorithm can equivalently be described by formulating the problem using a bipartite graph.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] We have a complete bipartite graph $G=(S,T;E)$ with n worker vertices (S) and n job vertices (T), and the edges (E) each have a cost $c(i,j)$ .
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] We want to find a perfect matching with a minimum total cost.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] Let us call a function $y:(S\cup T)\to \mathbb {R}$ a **potential** if $y(i)+y(j)\leq c(i,j)$ for each $i\in S,j\in T$ .
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] The cost of each perfect matching is at least the value of each potential.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] This can be seen by first noticing that the total cost of the matching is the sum of costs of all edges it contains.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] The cost of each edge is at least the sum of potentials of its endpoints.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] Since the matching is perfect, each vertex is an endpoint of exactly one edge.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] Hence, the total cost is at least the total potential.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] The Hungarian method finds a perfect matching and a potential such that the matching cost equals the potential value.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] This proves that both of them are optimal.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] In fact, the Hungarian method finds a perfect matching of **tight edges**: an edge $ij$ is called tight for a potential y if $y(i)+y(j)=c(i,j)$ .
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] Let us denote the subgraph of **tight** edges by $G_{y}$ .
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] The cost of a perfect matching in $G_{y}$ (if there is one) equals the value of y.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] During the algorithm we maintain a potential y and an orientation of $G_{y}$ (denoted by ${\overrightarrow {G_{y}}}$ ) which has the property that the edges oriented from T to S form a matching M.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] Initially, y is 0 everywhere, and all edges are oriented from S to T (so M is empty).
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] In each step, either we modify y so that its value increases, or modify the orientation to obtain a matching with more edges.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] We maintain the invariant that all the edges of M are tight.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] In a general step, let $R_{S}\subseteq S$ and $R_{T}\subseteq T$ be the vertices not covered by M (so $R_{S}$ consists of the vertices in S with no incoming edge and $R_{T}$ consists of the vertices in T with no outgoing edge).
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] Let Z be the set of vertices reachable in ${\overrightarrow {G_{y}}}$ from $R_{S}$ by a directed path.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] This can be computed by breadth-first search.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] If $R_{T}\cap Z$ is nonempty, then reverse the orientation of all edges along a directed path in ${\overrightarrow {G_{y}}}$ from $R_{S}$ to $R_{T}$ .
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] Thus the size of the corresponding matching increases by 1.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] Δ is well defined because at least one such edge $ij$ must exist whenever the matching is not yet of maximum possible size (see the following section); it is positive because there are no tight edges between $Z\cap S$ and $T\setminus Z$ .
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] Increase y by Δ on the vertices of $Z\cap S$ and decrease y by Δ on the vertices of $Z\cap T$ .
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] The resulting y is still a potential, and although the graph $G_{y}$ changes, it still contains M (see the next subsections).
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] By the definition of Δ the set Z of vertices reachable from $R_{S}$ increases (note that the number of tight edges does not necessarily increase).
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] If the vertex added to $Z\cap T$ is unmatched (that is, it is also in $R_{T}$ ), then at the next iteration the graph will have an augmenting path.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] We repeat these steps until M is a perfect matching, in which case it gives a minimum cost assignment.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] The running time of this version of the method is $O(n^{4})$ : M is augmented n times, and in a phase where M is unchanged, there are at most n potential changes (since Z increases every time).
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] The time sufficient for a potential change is $O(n^{2})$ .
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] We must show that as long as the matching is not of maximum possible size, the algorithm is always able to make progress — that is, to either increase the number of matched edges, or tighten at least one edge.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] If M is of maximum possible size, we are of course finished.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] Otherwise, by Berge's lemma, there must exist an augmenting path P with respect to M in the underlying graph G.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] However, this path may not exist in $G_{y}$ : Although every even-numbered edge in P is tight by the definition of M, odd-numbered edges may be loose and thus absent from $G_{y}$ .
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] One endpoint of P is in $R_{S}$ , the other in $R_{T}$ ; w.l.o.g., suppose it begins in $R_{S}$ .
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] If every edge on P is tight, then it remains an augmenting path in $G_{y}$ and we are done.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] Otherwise, let $uv$ be the first loose edge on P.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] If $v\notin Z$ then we have found a loose-tailed path and we are done.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] Otherwise, v is reachable from some other path Q of tight edges from a vertex in $R_{S}$ .
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] Let $P_{v}$ be the subpath of P beginning at v and continuing to the end, and let $P'$ be the path formed by traveling along Q until a vertex on $P_{v}$ is reached, and then continuing to the end of $P_{v}$ .
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] Observe that $P'$ is an augmenting path in G with at least one fewer loose edge than P.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] P can be replaced with $P'$ and this reasoning process iterated (formally, using induction on the number of loose edges) until either an augmenting path in $G_{y}$ or a loose-tailed path in G is found.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] To show that every edge in M remains after adjusting y, it suffices to show that for an arbitrary edge in M, either both of its endpoints, or neither of them, are in Z.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] To this end let $vu$ be an edge in M from T to S.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] It is easy to see that if v is in Z then u must be too, since every edge in M is tight.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] Now suppose, toward contradiction, that $u\in Z$ but $v\notin Z$ . u itself cannot be in $R_{S}$ because it is the endpoint of a matched edge, so there must be some directed path of tight edges from a vertex in $R_{S}$ to u.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] This path must avoid v, since that is by assumption not in Z, so the vertex immediately preceding u in this path is some other vertex $v'\in T$ . $v'u$ is a tight edge from T to S and is thus in M.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] But then M contains two edges that share the vertex u, contradicting the fact that M is a matching.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] Thus every edge in M has either both endpoints or neither endpoint in Z.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] To show that y remains a potential after being adjusted, it suffices to show that no edge has its total potential increased beyond its cost.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] This is already established for edges in M by the preceding paragraph, so consider an arbitrary edge uv from S to T.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] If $y(u)$ is increased by Δ, then either $v\in Z\cap T$ , in which case $y(v)$ is decreased by Δ, leaving the total potential of the edge unchanged, or $v\in T\setminus Z$ , in which case the definition of Δ guarantees that $y(u)+y(v)+\Delta \leq c(u,v)$ .
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] Suppose there are J jobs and W workers ( $J\leq W$ ).
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] We describe how to compute for each prefix of jobs the minimum total cost to assign each of these jobs to distinct workers.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] Specifically, we add the j th job and update the total cost in time $O(jW)$ , yielding an overall time complexity of $O\left(\sum _{j=1}^{J}jW\right)=O(J^{2}W)$ .
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] Note that this is better than $O(W^{3})$ when the number of jobs is small relative to the number of workers.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] We use the same notation as the previous section, though we modify their definitions as necessary.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] Let $S_{j}$ denote the set of the first j jobs and T denote the set of all workers.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] Note that such potentials certify the optimality of the matching.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] During the j th step, we add the j th job to $S_{j-1}$ to form $S_{j}$ and initialize $Z=\{j\}$ .
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] At all times, every vertex in Z will be reachable from the j th job in $G_{y}$ .
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] and $w_{\text{next}}$ denote any w at which the minimum is attained.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] After adjusting the potentials in the way described in the previous section, there is now a tight edge from Z to $w_{\text{next}}$ .
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] Recomputing $\Delta$ and $w_{\text{next}}$ after changing the potentials and Z also can be done in $O(W)$ time.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] Case 1 can occur at most $j-1$ times before case 2 occurs and the procedure terminates, yielding the overall time complexity of $O(jW)$ .
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] For convenience of implementation, the code below adds an additional worker $w_{W}$ such that $y(w_{W})$ stores the negation of the sum of all $\Delta$ computed so far.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] After the j th job is added and the matching updated, the cost of the current matching equals the sum of all $\Delta$ computed so far, or $-y(w_{W})$ .
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] This code is adapted from e-maxx :: algo.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] The Hungarian algorithm can be seen to be equivalent to the successive shortest path algorithm for minimum cost flow, where the reweighting technique from Johnson's algorithm is used to find the shortest paths.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] The implementation from the previous section is rewritten below in such a way as to emphasize this connection; it can be checked that the potentials h for workers $0\dots W-1$ are equal to the potentials y from the previous solution up to a constant offset.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] This variant of the algorithm follows the formulation given by Flood, and later described more explicitly by Munkres, who proved it runs in ${\mathcal {O}}(n^{4})$ time.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] where $c(i,j)$ is the original cost matrix and $y(i),y(j)$ are the potentials from the graph interpretation.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] Changing the potentials corresponds to adding or subtracting from rows or columns of this matrix.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] The algorithm starts with $a_{ij}=c(i,j)$ .
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] As such, it can be viewed as taking the original cost matrix and modifying it.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] where a, b, c and d are workers who have to perform tasks 1, 2, 3 and 4. a1, a2, a3, and a4 denote the penalties incurred when worker "a" does task 1, 2, 3, and 4 respectively.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] The problem is equivalent to assigning each worker a unique task such that the total penalty is minimized.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] Note that each task can only be worked on by one worker.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] This also leads to at least one zero in each row.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] As such, a naive greedy algorithm can attempt to assign all workers a task with a penalty of zero.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] The zeros above would be the assigned tasks.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] Worst-case there are n! combinations to try, since multiple zeroes can appear in a row if multiple elements are the minimum.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] So at some point this naive algorithm should be short circuited.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] Sometimes it may turn out that the matrix at this stage cannot be used for assigning, as is the case for the matrix below.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] To overcome this, we repeat the above procedure for all columns (i.e.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] **the minimum element in each column is subtracted from all the elements in that column**) and then check if an assignment with penalty 0 is possible.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] In most situations this will give the result, but if it is still not possible then we need to keep going.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] For each row, try to assign an arbitrary zero.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] Assigned tasks are represented by starring a zero.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] Note that assignments can't be in the same row or column.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] We could end with another assignment if we choose another ordering of the rows and columns.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] Cover all columns containing a (starred) zero.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] Find a non-covered zero and prime it (mark it with a prime symbol).
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] If no such zero can be found, meaning all zeroes are covered, skip to step 5.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] Substep 2: Find a primed zero on the corresponding row (there should always be one).
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] We add to the path the first zero of Row 1, then the second zero of Row 1, then we are done.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] All zeros are now covered with a minimal number of rows and columns.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] The aforementioned detailed description is *just one way* to draw the minimum number of lines to cover all the 0s.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] If the number of starred zeros is n (or in the general case $min(n,m)$ , where n is the number of people and m is the number of jobs), the algorithm terminates.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] See the Result subsection below on how to interpret the results.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] Otherwise, find the lowest uncovered value.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] Subtract this from every uncovered element and add it to every element covered by two lines.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] This is equivalent to subtracting a number from all rows which are not covered and adding the same number to all columns which are covered.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] These operations do not change optimal assignments.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] If following this specific version of the algorithm, the starred zeros form the minimum assignment.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] From Kőnig's theorem, the minimum number of lines (minimum vertex cover) will be n (the size of maximum matching).
[src:hungarian-algorithm/hungarian-algorithm] Thus, when n lines are required, minimum cost assignment can be found by looking at only zeroes in the matrix.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] In the mathematical area of graph theory, **Kőnig's theorem**, proved by Dénes Kőnig (1931), describes an equivalence between the maximum matching problem and the minimum vertex cover problem in bipartite graphs.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] It was discovered independently, also in 1931, by Jenő Egerváry in the more general case of weighted graphs.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] A vertex cover in a graph is a set of vertices that includes at least one endpoint of every edge, and a vertex cover is *minimum* if no other vertex cover has fewer vertices.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] A matching in a graph is a set of edges no two of which share an endpoint, and a matching is *maximum* if no other matching has more edges.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] It is obvious from the definition that any vertex-cover set must be at least as large as any matching set (since for every edge in the matching, at least one vertex is needed in the cover).
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] In particular, the minimum vertex cover set is at least as large as the maximum matching set.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] Kőnig's theorem states that, in any bipartite graph, the minimum vertex cover set and the maximum matching set have in fact the same size.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] The bipartite graph shown in the above illustration has 14 vertices; a matching with six edges is shown in blue, and a vertex cover with six vertices is shown in red.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] There can be no smaller vertex cover, because any vertex cover has to include at least one endpoint of each matched edge (as well as of every other edge), so this is a minimum vertex cover.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] Similarly, there can be no larger matching, because any matched edge has to include at least one endpoint in the vertex cover, so this is a maximum matching.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] Kőnig's theorem states that the equality between the sizes of the matching and the cover (in this example, both numbers are six) applies more generally to any bipartite graph.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] The following proof provides a way of constructing a minimum vertex cover from a maximum matching.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] Let $G=(V,E)$ be a bipartite graph and let $A,B$ be the two parts of the vertex set V .
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] Suppose that M is a maximum matching for G .
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] Construct the flow network $G'_{\infty }$ derived from G in such way that there are edges of capacity 1 from the source s to every vertex $a\in A$ and from every vertex $b\in B$ to the sink t , and of capacity $+\infty$ from a to b for any $(a,b)\in E$ .
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] The size $|M|$ of the maximum matching in G is the size of a maximum flow in $G'_{\infty }$ , which, in turn, is the size of a minimum cut in the network $G'_{\infty }$ , as follows from the max-flow min-cut theorem.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] Then the minimum cut is composed only of edges going from s to $A_{T}$ or from $B_{S}$ to t , as any edge from $A_{S}$ to $B_{T}$ would make the size of the cut infinite.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] Therefore, the size of the minimum cut is equal to $|A_{T}|+|B_{S}|$ .
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] On the other hand, $A_{T}\cup B_{S}$ is a vertex cover, as any edge that is not incident to vertices from $A_{T}$ and $B_{S}$ must be incident to a pair of vertices from $A_{S}$ and $B_{T}$ , which would contradict the fact that there are no edges between $A_{S}$ and $B_{T}$ .
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] Thus, $A_{T}\cup B_{S}$ is a minimum vertex cover of G .
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] No vertex in a vertex cover can cover more than one edge of M (because the edge half-overlap would prevent M from being a matching in the first place), so if a vertex cover with $|M|$ vertices can be constructed, it must be a minimum cover.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] To construct such a cover, let U be the set of unmatched vertices in A (possibly empty), and let Z be the set of vertices that are either in U or are connected to U by alternating paths (paths that alternate between edges that are in the matching and edges that are not in the matching).
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] Every edge e in E either belongs to an alternating path (and has a right endpoint in K ), or it has a left endpoint in K .
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] For, if e is matched but not in an alternating path, then its left endpoint cannot be in an alternating path (because two matched edges can not share a vertex) and thus belongs to $A\setminus Z$ .
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] Alternatively, if e is unmatched but not in an alternating path, then its left endpoint cannot be in an alternating path, for such a path could be extended by adding e to it.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] Additionally, every vertex in K is an endpoint of a matched edge.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] For, every vertex in $A\setminus Z$ is matched because Z is a superset of U , the set of unmatched left vertices.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] And every vertex in $B\cap Z$ must also be matched, for if there existed an alternating path to an unmatched vertex then changing the matching by removing the matched edges from this path and adding the unmatched edges in their place would increase the size of the matching.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] However, no matched edge can have both of its endpoints in K .
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] Thus, K is a vertex cover of cardinality equal to M , and must be a minimum vertex cover.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] Similarly we define a fractional vertex-cover - an assignment of a non-negative weight to each vertex, such that the sum of weights in each edge is at least 1 (an integral vertex-cover is a special case of a fractional vertex-cover in which the weights are in {0,1}).
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] where **x** is a vector of size |*E*| in which each element represents the weight of an edge in the fractional matching.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] **1**E is a vector of |*E*| ones, so the first line indicates the size of the matching.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] **0***E* is a vector of |*E*| zeros, so the second line indicates the constraint that the weights are non-negative.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] **1**V is a vector of |*V*| ones and **A***G* is the incidence matrix of *G,* so the third line indicates the constraint that the sum of weights near each vertex is at most 1.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] where **y** is a vector of size |V| in which each element represents the weight of a vertex in the fractional cover.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] Here, the first line is the size of the cover, the second line represents the non-negativity of the weights, and the third line represents the requirement that the sum of weights near each edge must be at least 1.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] Now, the minimum fractional cover LP is exactly the dual linear program of the maximum fractional matching LP.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] Therefore, by the LP duality theorem, both programs have the same solution.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] What makes bipartite graphs special is that, in bipartite graphs, both these linear programs have optimal solutions in which all variable values are integers.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] This follows from the fact that in the fractional matching polytope of a bipartite graph, all extreme points have only integer coordinates, and the same is true for the fractional vertex-cover polytope.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] The constructive proof described above provides an algorithm for producing a minimum vertex cover given a maximum matching.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] Thus, the Hopcroft–Karp algorithm for finding maximum matchings in bipartite graphs may also be used to solve the vertex cover problem efficiently in these graphs.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] Despite the equivalence of the two problems from the point of view of exact solutions, they are not equivalent for approximation algorithms.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] Bipartite maximum matchings can be approximated arbitrarily accurately in constant time by distributed algorithms; in contrast, approximating the minimum vertex cover of a bipartite graph requires at least logarithmic time.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] In the graph shown in the introduction take L to be the set of vertices in the bottom layer of the diagram and R to be the set of vertices in the top layer of the diagram.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] From left to right label the vertices in the bottom layer with the numbers 1, ..., 7 and label the vertices in the top layer with the numbers 8, ..., 14.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] The set U of unmatched vertices from L is {1}.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] For graphs that are not bipartite, the minimum vertex cover may be larger than the maximum matching.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] Moreover, the two problems are very different in complexity: maximum matchings can be found in polynomial time for any graph, while minimum vertex cover is NP-complete.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] The complement of a vertex cover in any graph is an independent set, so a minimum vertex cover is complementary to a maximum independent set; finding maximum independent sets is another NP-complete problem.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] The equivalence between matching and covering articulated in Kőnig's theorem allows minimum vertex covers and maximum independent sets to be computed in polynomial time for bipartite graphs, despite the NP-completeness of these problems for more general graph families.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] Kőnig's theorem is named after the Hungarian mathematician Dénes Kőnig.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] However, Bondy & Murty (1976) attribute Kőnig's theorem itself to a later paper of Kőnig (1931).
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] According to Biggs, Lloyd & Wilson (1976), Kőnig attributed the idea of studying matchings in bipartite graphs to his father, mathematician Gyula Kőnig.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] In Hungarian, Kőnig's name has a double acute accent, but his theorem is sometimes spelled (incorrectly) in German characters, with an umlaut.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] Kőnig's theorem is equivalent to many other min-max theorems in graph theory and combinatorics, such as Hall's marriage theorem and Dilworth's theorem.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] Since bipartite matching is a special case of maximum flow, the theorem also results from the max-flow min-cut theorem.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] A graph is said to be perfect if, in every induced subgraph, the chromatic number equals the size of the largest clique.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] Any bipartite graph is perfect, because each of its subgraphs is either bipartite or independent; in a bipartite graph that is not independent the chromatic number and the size of the largest clique are both two while in an independent set the chromatic number and clique number are both one.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] A graph is perfect if and only if its complement is perfect, and Kőnig's theorem can be seen as equivalent to the statement that the complement of a bipartite graph is perfect.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] Conversely, Kőnig's theorem proves the perfection of the complements of bipartite graphs, a result proven in a more explicit form by Gallai (1958).
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] One can also connect Kőnig's line coloring theorem to a different class of perfect graphs, the line graphs of bipartite graphs.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] If *G* is a graph, the line graph *L*(*G*) has a vertex for each edge of *G*, and an edge for each pair of adjacent edges in *G*.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] Thus, the chromatic number of *L*(*G*) equals the chromatic index of *G*.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] If *G* is bipartite, the cliques in *L*(*G*) are exactly the sets of edges in *G* sharing a common endpoint.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] Now Kőnig's line coloring theorem, stating that the chromatic index equals the maximum vertex degree in any bipartite graph, can be interpreted as stating that the line graph of a bipartite graph is perfect.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] Since line graphs of bipartite graphs are perfect, the complements of line graphs of bipartite graphs are also perfect.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] A clique in the complement of the line graph of *G* is just a matching in *G*.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] And a coloring in the complement of the line graph of *G*, when *G* is bipartite, is a partition of the edges of *G* into subsets of edges sharing a common endpoint; the endpoints shared by each of these subsets form a vertex cover for *G*.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] Therefore, Kőnig's theorem itself can also be interpreted as stating that the complements of line graphs of bipartite graphs are perfect.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] Konig's theorem can be extended to weighted graphs.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] Jenő Egerváry (1931) considered graphs in which each edge *e* has a non-negative integer weight *we*.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] The **w-***weight of a matching* is the sum of weights of the edges participating in the matching.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] A ***w-**vertex-cover* is a multiset of vertices ("multiset" means that each vertex may appear several times), in which each edge *e* is adjacent to at least *we* vertices.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] As in the proof of Konig's theorem, the LP duality theorem implies that the optimal values are equal (for any graph), and the fact that the graph is bipartite implies that these programs have optimal solutions in which all values are integers.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] One can consider a graph in which each vertex *v* has a non-negative integer weight *bv*.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] The ***b**-weight* of a vertex-cover is the sum of *bv* for all *v* in the cover.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/kőnig-s-theorem-graph-theory] A ***b**-matching* is an assignment of a non-negative integral weight to each edge, such that the sum of weights of edges adjacent to any vertex *v* is at most *bv*.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] In the mathematical discipline of graph theory, a **matching** or **independent edge set** in an undirected graph is a set of edges without common vertices.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] In other words, a subset of the edges is a matching if each vertex appears in at most one edge of that matching.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] Finding a largest matching in a bipartite graph can be treated as a network flow problem.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] Finding a largest matching in a general graph is much more difficult; it can be done using Edmonds' blossom algorithm.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] Given a graph *G* = (*V*, *E*), a **matching** *M* in *G* is a set of pairwise non-adjacent edges, none of which are loops; that is, no two edges share common vertices.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] M is a matching *of* $U\subseteq V$ if every vertex in U is incident with an edge in M .
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] A vertex is **matched** (or **saturated**) if it is an endpoint of one of the edges in the matching.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] Otherwise the vertex is **unmatched** (or **unsaturated**).
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] A **maximal matching** is a matching *M* of a graph *G* that is not a subset of any other matching.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] A matching *M* of a graph *G* is maximal if every edge in *G* has a non-empty intersection with at least one edge in *M*.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] The following figure shows examples of maximal matchings (red) in three graphs.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] A **maximum matching** (also known as maximum-cardinality matching) is a matching that contains the largest possible number of edges.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] The **matching number** $\nu (G)$ of a graph G is the size of a maximum matching.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] Every maximum matching is maximal, but not every maximal matching is a maximum matching.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] The following figure shows examples of maximum matchings in the same three graphs.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] A **perfect matching** is a matching that matches all vertices of the graph.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] That is, a matching is perfect if every vertex of the graph is incident to an edge of the matching.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] Every perfect matching is maximum and hence maximal.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] In some literature, the term **complete matching** is used.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] In the above figure, only part (b) shows a perfect matching.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] A perfect matching is also a minimum-size edge cover.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] Thus, the size of a maximum matching is no larger than the size of a minimum edge cover: ⁠ $\nu (G)\leq \rho (G)$ ⁠.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] A graph can only contain a perfect matching when the graph has an even number of vertices.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] A **near-perfect matching** is one in which exactly one vertex is unmatched.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] Clearly, a graph can only contain a near-perfect matching when the graph has an odd number of vertices, and near-perfect matchings are maximum matchings.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] In the above figure, part (c) shows a near-perfect matching.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] If every vertex is unmatched by some near-perfect matching, then the graph is called factor-critical.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] An **induced matching** is a matching that is the edge set of an induced subgraph.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] Given a matching *M*, an **alternating path** is a path that begins with an unmatched vertex and whose edges belong alternately to the matching and not to the matching.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] An **augmenting path** is an alternating path that starts from and ends on free (unmatched) vertices.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] Berge's lemma states that a matching *M* is maximum if and only if there is no augmenting path with respect to M *.* Using Berge's lemma, we can start from any matching M and repeatedly apply augmenting paths until no more augmenting paths are found.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] This reduces the problem of finding a large matching to finding augmented paths.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] In any graph without isolated vertices, the sum of the matching number and the edge covering number equals the number of vertices.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] If there is a perfect matching, then both the matching number and the edge cover number are |*V* | / 2.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] Kőnig's theorem states that, in bipartite graphs, the maximum matching is equal in size to the minimum vertex cover.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] Via this result, the minimum vertex cover, maximum independent set, and maximum vertex biclique problems may be solved in polynomial time for bipartite graphs.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] Hall's marriage theorem provides a characterization of bipartite graphs which have a perfect matching and Tutte's theorem on perfect matchings provides a characterization for arbitrary graphs.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] A spectral characterization of the matching number of a graph is given by Hassani Monfared and Mallik as follows: Let G be a graph on n vertices, and $\lambda _{1}>\lambda _{2}>\ldots >\lambda _{k}>0$ be k distinct nonzero purely imaginary numbers where $2k\leq n$ .
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] Then the matching number of G is k if and only if (a) there is a real skew-symmetric matrix A with graph G and eigenvalues $\pm \lambda _{1},\pm \lambda _{2},\ldots ,\pm \lambda _{k}$ and $n-2k$ zeros, and (b) all real skew-symmetric matrices with graph G have at most $2k$ nonzero eigenvalues.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] Note that the (simple) graph of a real symmetric or skew-symmetric matrix A of order n has n vertices and edges given by the nonozero off-diagonal entries of A .
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] In particular, this shows that any maximal matching is a 2-approximation of a maximum matching and also a 2-approximation of a minimum maximal matching.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] This inequality is tight: for example, if *G* is a path with 3 edges and 4 vertices, the size of a minimum maximal matching is 1 and the size of a maximum matching is 2.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] A generating function of the number of *k*-edge matchings in a graph is called a matching polynomial.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] Let *G* be a graph and *mk* be the number of *k*-edge matchings.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] where *n* is the number of vertices in the graph.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] Each type has its uses; for more information see the article on matching polynomials.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] A fundamental problem in combinatorial optimization is finding a *maximum matching*.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] This problem has various algorithms for different classes of graphs.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] In an *unweighted bipartite graph*, the optimization problem is to find a maximum cardinality matching.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] The problem is solved by the Hopcroft-Karp algorithm in time *O*(√*V**E*) time, and there are more efficient randomized algorithms, approximation algorithms, and algorithms for special classes of graphs such as bipartite planar graphs, as described in the main article.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] In a *weighted* *bipartite graph,* the optimization problem is to find a maximum-weight matching; a dual problem is to find a minimum-weight matching.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] This problem is often called **maximum weighted bipartite matching**, or the **assignment problem**.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] The Hungarian algorithm solves the assignment problem and it was one of the beginnings of combinatorial optimization algorithms.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] It uses a modified shortest path search in the augmenting path algorithm.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] If the Bellman–Ford algorithm is used for this step, the running time of the Hungarian algorithm becomes $O(V^{2}E)$ , or the edge cost can be shifted with a potential to achieve $O(V^{2}\log {V}+VE)$ running time with the Dijkstra algorithm and Fibonacci heap.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] In a *non-bipartite weighted graph*, the problem of **maximum weight matching** can be solved in time $O(V^{2}E)$ using Edmonds' blossom algorithm.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] A maximal matching can be found with a simple greedy algorithm.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] A maximum matching is also a maximal matching, and hence it is possible to find a *largest* maximal matching in polynomial time.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] It is also possible to find a maximum matching with the use of fast matrix multiplication algorithms in the time $O({n^{\omega }})$ for $~2.37\leq \omega <3$ .
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] However, no polynomial-time algorithm is known for finding a **minimum maximal matching**, that is, a maximal matching that contains the *smallest* possible number of edges.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] A maximal matching with *k* edges is an edge dominating set with *k* edges.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] Conversely, if we are given a minimum edge dominating set with *k* edges, we can construct a maximal matching with *k* edges in polynomial time.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] Therefore, the problem of finding a minimum maximal matching is essentially equal to the problem of finding a minimum edge dominating set.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] Both of these two optimization problems are known to be NP-hard; the decision versions of these problems are classical examples of NP-complete problems.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] Both problems can be approximated within factor 2 in polynomial time: simply find an arbitrary maximal matching *M*.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] The number of matchings in a graph is known as the Hosoya index of the graph.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] It is #P-complete to compute this quantity, even for bipartite graphs.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] It is also #P-complete to count perfect matchings, even in bipartite graphs, because computing the permanent of an arbitrary 0–1 matrix (another #P-complete problem) is the same as computing the number of perfect matchings in the bipartite graph having the given matrix as its biadjacency matrix.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] However, there exists a fully polynomial time randomized approximation scheme for counting the number of bipartite matchings.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] A remarkable theorem of Kasteleyn states that the number of perfect matchings in a planar graph can be computed exactly in polynomial time via the FKT algorithm.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] The number of perfect matchings in a complete graph *K**n* (with *n* even) is given by the double factorial (*n* − 1)!!.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] The numbers of matchings in complete graphs, without constraining the matchings to be perfect, are given by the telephone numbers.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] The number of perfect matchings in a graph is also known as the hafnian of its adjacency matrix.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] One of the basic problems in matching theory is to find in a given graph all edges that may be extended to a maximum matching in the graph (such edges are called maximally matchable edges, or **allowed** edges).
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] The problem of developing an online algorithm for matching was first considered by Richard M.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] Karp, Umesh Vazirani, and Vijay Vazirani in 1990.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] In the online setting, nodes on one side of the bipartite graph ("clients") arrive one at a time and must either be immediately matched to the other side of the graph ("servers") or discarded.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] This is a natural generalization of the secretary problem and has applications to online ad auctions.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] A simple greedy algorithm is 1/2-competitive.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] For the unweighted maximization case with a random arrival model, Karp, Vazirani and Vazirani gave a randomized algorithm that attains a competitive ratio of 0.632.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/matching-graph-theory] The problem was also studied in a model where clients may switch servers in order to improve the matching, and the goal is to economize on the number of switches while achieving a maximum matching.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/maximum-cardinality-matching] In graph theory, a **maximum-cardinality matching** is a special kind of subgraph useful in many computational contexts.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/maximum-cardinality-matching] Given a graph G, a matching is a subgraph where no two edges share a vertex.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/maximum-cardinality-matching] The cardinality of the matching is the number of edges in the subgraph, and the maximum cardinality is the largest number of edges a matching can contain.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/maximum-cardinality-matching] A matching for a given graph is a **maximum-cardinality matching** if its cardinality is this maximum cardinality.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/maximum-cardinality-matching] If we think of each edge as "covering" the vertices it connects exactly once, then a maximal matching is also the largest non-overlapping cover of the graph.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/maximum-cardinality-matching] If all the vertices are covered, we call it a perfect matching.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/maximum-cardinality-matching] For finite graphs, a maximum-cardinality matching always exists, but is not usually unique.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/maximum-cardinality-matching] The cardinality of the matching is never more than half the number of vertices and also never more than the number of edges.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/maximum-cardinality-matching] An important special case of the maximum-cardinality matching problem is when G is a bipartite graph representing a binary relation, whose vertices V are partitioned between left vertices in X and right vertices in Y, and edges in E always connect a left vertex to a right vertex.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/maximum-cardinality-matching] In this case, the problem can be efficiently solved with simpler algorithms than in the general case.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/maximum-cardinality-matching] The calculation of a **maximum matching** for a given graph is a fundamental task in computational graph theory.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/maximum-cardinality-matching] There are nonconstructive characterization theorems for the size of a maximum matching.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/maximum-cardinality-matching] This article is about computation of maximum matchings.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/maximum-cardinality-matching] The simplest way to compute a maximum-cardinality matching is to follow the Ford–Fulkerson algorithm.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/maximum-cardinality-matching] This algorithm solves the more general problem of computing the maximum flow.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/maximum-cardinality-matching] A bipartite graph (*X* + *Y*, *E*) can be converted to a flow network as follows.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/maximum-cardinality-matching] Since each edge in the network has integral capacity, there exists a maximum flow where all flows are integers; these integers must be either 0 or 1 since the all capacities are 1.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/maximum-cardinality-matching] Each integral flow defines a matching in which an edge is in the matching if and only if its flow is 1.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/maximum-cardinality-matching] The Ford–Fulkerson algorithm proceeds by repeatedly finding an augmenting path from some *x* ∈ *X* to some *y* ∈ Y and updating the matching M by taking the symmetric difference of that path with M (assuming such a path exists).
[src:hungarian-algorithm/maximum-cardinality-matching] As each path can be found in *O*(*E*) time, the running time is *O*(*VE*), and the maximum matching consists of the edges of E that carry flow from X to Y.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/maximum-cardinality-matching] An improvement to this algorithm is given by the more elaborate Hopcroft–Karp algorithm, which searches for multiple augmenting paths simultaneously.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/maximum-cardinality-matching] This algorithm runs in $O({\sqrt {V}}E)$ time.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/maximum-cardinality-matching] The blossom algorithm finds a maximum-cardinality matching in general (not necessarily bipartite) graphs.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/maximum-cardinality-matching] A better performance of *O*(√*V**E*) for general graphs, matching the performance of the Hopcroft–Karp algorithm on bipartite graphs, can be achieved with the much more complicated algorithm of Micali and Vazirani.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/maximum-cardinality-matching] The same bound was achieved by an algorithm by Blum and an algorithm by Gabow and Tarjan.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/maximum-cardinality-matching] An alternative approach uses randomization and is based on the fast matrix multiplication algorithm.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/maximum-cardinality-matching] This gives a randomized algorithm for general graphs with complexity $O(V^{2.372})$ .
[src:hungarian-algorithm/maximum-cardinality-matching] This is better in theory for sufficiently dense graphs, but in practice the algorithm is slower.
[src:hungarian-algorithm/maximum-cardinality-matching] Other algorithms for the task are reviewed by Duan and Pettie (see Table I).
[src:hungarian-algorithm/maximum-cardinality-matching] In terms of approximation algorithms, they also point out that the blossom algorithm and the algorithms by Micali and Vazirani can be seen as approximation algorithms running in linear time for any fixed error bound.
